<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06292011 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06292011 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  COMPUTER; MANUFACTURING; COMPANY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Making good on its warning last month that red ink was on the way, SeagateTechnology Inc. on Thursday reported a $47.8 million loss for its firstquarter, nearly double what some people had expected.;   Like all other diskdrive manufacturers, Seagate is facing a slowdown in demand for its productsas well as an intense price war because of excess capacity. Only two of theindustry's six major drive manufacturers are expected to be profitable thisquarter, and one of the lucky pair, Conner Peripherals Inc., on Wednesdayreported a drop in profits as well as the layoff of 8 percent of its employees.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  RED INK AT SEAGATE: $48 MILLION  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Seagate, located in Scotts Valley, has responded to the recent dismalmarketplace with a series of harsh actions in the past three months, layingoff more than 1,600 workers, postponing plans for a new plant in Ireland andeven sacking its president, David Mitchell.;   When it warned last month of acoming loss, some analysts estimated it would be about $25 million.;   Thecompany on Thursday reported that for the period ending Sept. 30, net saleswere $620 million, down from the $630 million of the year before. The net lossamounted to 72 cents per share, compared with profits of $13.9 million, or 22cents a share, from the year before.;   In Over-the-Counter trading thatpreceded the late-afternoon announcement, shares in Seagate rose 13 cents toclose at $8.50.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  LEE GOMES, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911018  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  238  </WORD.CT><DATELI